result.execSummary:
The defendant Deandre Alton Williams was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • 2nd-Degree Recklessly Endangering Safety, a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.30(2).
  • Vehicle Operator Flee/Elude Officer, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.04(3).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Deandre Alton Williams in court with attorney Colleen A Taylor.  Defendant Deandre Alton Williams in custody, produced.  Annie Louk appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Case in Court for Plea and Sentencing hearing.  Parties have reached an agreement. State places offer on the record. Defense and defendant are in agreement.

Pursuant to negotiations and on the Motion of the State, Court Ordered Count Three DISMISSED BUT READ IN for the purpose of sentencing.

AS TO COUNT ONE : Defendant changes plea(s) to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to plea, advised of Constitutional Rights and the maximum penalties. Defendant further advised that if not a US citizen, deportation is possible. Court found that the defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived rights.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights form, Addendum, and Elements/Jury Instructions received and filed. Parties stipulate to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea(s).  Court found defendant GUILTY and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  

AS TO COUNT TWO : Defendant changes plea(s) to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to plea, advised of Constitutional Rights and the maximum penalties. Defendant further advised that if not a US citizen, deportation is possible. Court found that the defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived rights.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights form, Addendum, and Elements/Jury Instructions received and filed. Parties stipulate to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea(s).  Court found defendant GUILTY and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  

AS TO COUNT THREE : Dismissed and read in for sentencing. 

*Court advised due to felony conviction the defendant is prohibited from firearm possession, body armor, and defendant's voting rights are suspended and may not vote until civil rights are restored.

Sentencing proceeded. Due to technical/internet issues case, case is passed to the afternoon.  Parties to reconvene at 1:15 pm.

CASE RECALLED 1:13 pm
Appearances remain the same.

Sentencing proceeded. State has complied with victim notification. Statements by parties and defendant. 

AS TO COUNT ONE : The court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM term in the Wisconsin State Prison of 72 MONTHS, consecutive to any other sentence, with credit for 127 DAYS time served, the term of INITIAL CONFINEMENT is 36 MONTHS and the term of EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 36 MONTHS. Court STAYED sentence and placed defendant on PROBATION for 2 YEARS, concurrent to Count 2.

AS TO COUNT TWO : The court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM term in the Wisconsin State Prison of 36 MONTHS, concurrent to Count 1, the term of INITIAL CONFINEMENT is 12 MONTHS and the term of EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 24 MONTHS. Court STAYED sentence and placed defendant on PROBATION for 2 YEARS, concurrent to Count 1.    *Court imposes the mandatory 6 MONTH revocation of driver's license.

The court sentenced the defendant to serve 10 MONTHS condition time in the House of Correction. After 6 months straight time, the Defendant shall then be eligible for Huber release for work, school and job search.

AS TO COUNT THREE : On State's motion, dismissed and read in. 

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION/EXTENDED SUPERVISION:
- Absolute sobriety.
- AODA assessment, comply with recommended treatment.
- No possession, use, sale, or distribution of any illegal drugs; no association with any location where illegal substances are consumed, packaged or sold.
- Undergo random urine screens (no right to refuse screens, refusal will be treated as a positive test result) and HOC time could result from a positive test.
- DNA sample and surcharge (unless previously done).
- Pay all applicable fees of supervision.
- No possession of any firearms or ammunition.
- Maintain or seek verifiable full time employment or education or vocational training.
- Comply with all rules of probation or extende supervision.
- Cooperate with agent.
- Restitution set at $0.00.
- All mandatory court costs, fees, and assessments to be paid during the period of probation. If revoked, to be paid out of defendant's prison funds at an amount to be determined by the DOC and as a condition of extended supervision. Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.

*Court finds defendant is NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program OR the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.
*Court advised defendant of right to seek post conviction relief.
*Court advised due to felony conviction the defendant is prohibited from firearm possession, ammunition, and defendant's voting rights are suspended and may not vote until civil rights are restored.
